<?php

return function (
    string $title,
    string $baseDescription,
    string $kind,
    string $period,
    string $location,
    string $classification = '',
): string {
    $overview = "OVERVIEW\n{$baseDescription}";

    $setting = "HISTORICAL SETTING\nTo understand {$title}, it is useful to place it within both Georgian geography and the larger history of the Caucasus. The date or period associated with this entry is {$period}, while its principal geographical connection is {$location}. Georgia has never developed in isolation. The Black Sea coast, the high Caucasus, the valleys of Kartli and Kakheti, and the routes toward Armenia, Anatolia, Iran, and the northern steppe created different local experiences while also binding the country to long-distance exchange. Political names changed over time: Colchis, Egrisi, Iberia, Kartli, Abkhazia, Tao-Klarjeti, Kakheti-Hereti, Imereti, Kartli-Kakheti, and the united Georgian kingdom each described a particular balance of territory and authority. A date therefore should not be treated as a detached fact. It belongs to a landscape of roads, rivers, fortresses, churches, farms, markets, noble estates, and neighboring powers. Reading the entry in this wider setting helps explain why the subject mattered to people at the time rather than only why it is remembered today.";

    $sources = "EVIDENCE AND SOURCES\nHistorical knowledge about {$title} is assembled from sources that answer different kinds of questions. Georgian chronicles preserve royal successions, campaigns, saints’ lives, foundation stories, and moral interpretations, but many were copied or compiled long after the events they describe. Armenian, Byzantine, Arabic, Persian, Ottoman, Russian, and European writers can provide independent details, although they also wrote for their own courts and audiences. Inscriptions are often closer in date and can identify patrons, titles, donations, construction campaigns, or official language. Archaeology contributes settlement layers, graves, ceramics, coins, tools, weapons, food remains, and evidence of destruction or rebuilding. Art history studies style, workshop practice, materials, and visual programs. Modern historians compare these records instead of accepting a single account without criticism. Silence is also evidence: missing records may reflect war, fragile materials, inaccessible archives, or the priorities of elite authors. A responsible interpretation distinguishes contemporary testimony, later tradition, scholarly reconstruction, and national memory.";

    $geography = "GEOGRAPHY, CONNECTIONS, AND DAILY LIFE\nThe meaning of {$title} also depends on ordinary life around the better-known rulers, monuments, battles, or objects. Most people lived through agriculture, herding, craft production, local trade, family obligations, and service to landlords, monasteries, towns, or the crown. Mountain and lowland economies were connected but followed different seasonal rhythms. Merchants moved salt, wine, grain, livestock, textiles, metals, ceramics, books, and luxury goods across political borders. Clergy and monks traveled between Georgian foundations in the Caucasus, Jerusalem, Sinai, Mount Athos, and the Byzantine world. Soldiers could include royal guards, noble retinues, local levies, highland fighters, mercenaries, and allied peoples. Women participated as landholders, donors, artisans, workers, nuns, queens, and transmitters of family memory even when chronicles mentioned them less often than men. Considering these social dimensions prevents the historical record from becoming only a list of kings and wars and shows how large changes affected communities unevenly.";

    if ($kind === 'artifact') {
        $material = "MATERIAL, MAKING, AND USE\nAs an artifact classified under {$classification}, {$title} should be examined as a physical object or built work before it is treated as an illustration of a story. Its makers had to select and prepare materials, master tools, organize labor, and follow practical as well as symbolic conventions. Stone records quarrying and carving; metal can reveal alloy, hammering, casting, welding, gilding, wear, and repair; manuscripts preserve parchment or paper, ink, pigment, ruling, handwriting, binding, and later annotations. Architecture records foundations, masonry phases, roofing, drainage, painting, reuse, and adaptation to terrain. An object’s function may also change. A sacred donation can become a museum piece, a weapon can become an heirloom, and a defensive tower can become protected heritage. Scratches, missing pieces, replacements, smoke, corrosion, and rebuilding are not merely damage. They are evidence of the generations that handled, valued, altered, forgot, rediscovered, and preserved the subject.";

        $comparison = "COMPARISON AND INTERPRETATION\nSpecialists understand {$title} by comparing it with securely dated examples from Georgia and neighboring regions. Similar letter forms can help date an inscription; construction joints can reveal separate building campaigns; coin hoards can establish circulation patterns; pigment analysis can identify workshop choices; and metallurgical study can distinguish local production from imported materials. Comparison must be careful, because resemblance does not automatically prove that one workshop copied another or that an object traveled from abroad. Georgian artisans repeatedly adapted international forms to local language, ritual, landscape, and patronage. The original archaeological or architectural context is especially important. An object recovered from a grave, church treasury, settlement floor, fortress, or private collection carries different evidence. When that context is lost, historians must state the uncertainty rather than invent a precise biography. This approach makes the archive more credible and teaches how conclusions are built from material clues.";

        $preservation = "PRESERVATION AND PUBLIC RESPONSIBILITY\nThe survival of {$title} cannot be taken for granted. Organic materials decay, metals corrode, stone cracks, paint fades, buildings suffer earthquakes and water, and objects can be displaced by war, theft, uncontrolled excavation, or the art market. Conservation begins with documentation: dimensions, photographs, condition reports, scientific analysis, ownership history, and the exact location of every intervention. Good treatment aims to stabilize rather than make an old object look artificially new. Digital records improve access but do not replace the original material. Museums, churches, local communities, archaeologists, archivists, conservators, and government agencies may have different responsibilities and priorities. Public interpretation should credit source communities and explain uncertainty, restoration, and disputed provenance. Protecting Georgian heritage also means maintaining historic landscapes and living traditions, not simply isolating attractive objects behind glass.";
    } else {
        $material = "CAUSES, ACTORS, AND DECISIONS\n{$title} did not arise from a single cause. Political ambition, dynastic marriage, taxation, military pressure, religious authority, trade routes, local rivalries, climate, population movement, and the choices of individual leaders could all interact. Powerful rulers appear prominently in written sources, yet their plans depended on nobles, clergy, town communities, farmers, soldiers, diplomats, craftspeople, and neighboring societies. Alliances could cross religious and linguistic boundaries, and the same family might cooperate with one empire while resisting another. Decisions that appear inevitable in hindsight were uncertain to participants. They acted with incomplete information, competing loyalties, and limited resources. Studying alternatives—what opponents wanted, why allies joined, and what options were rejected—makes the event more intelligible. It also prevents a simple heroic or tragic narrative from hiding negotiation, compromise, internal disagreement, and the practical work required to mobilize people and supplies.";

        $comparison = "CONSEQUENCES AND CHANGE OVER TIME\nThe consequences of {$title} unfolded at several speeds. Immediate results might include a new ruler, a captured city, a treaty, casualties, migration, taxation, or damage to farmland and buildings. Medium-term effects could alter noble power, church organization, military recruitment, commercial routes, language policy, or relations with neighboring states. Long-term significance was often created by later generations that selected the event as a turning point. Not every region experienced the same outcome, and official victory did not guarantee complete control on the ground. Continuities are therefore as important as change: families remained on their land, religious communities adapted, and older legal or cultural practices survived under new governments. Comparing conditions before, during, and after the event allows students to test claims about transformation. It also reveals unintended consequences that contemporary leaders could not have predicted.";

        $preservation = "MEMORY, HISTORIOGRAPHY, AND COMMEMORATION\nThe public memory of {$title} has been shaped by chronicles, church calendars, poetry, schoolbooks, monuments, anniversaries, political speeches, family stories, museum displays, and modern media. Commemoration can preserve knowledge and strengthen community, but it can also simplify a complicated past into a single lesson. Different periods emphasized different meanings: medieval authors often judged events through Christian kingship and moral order; imperial and Soviet scholarship used their own political frameworks; modern historians ask new questions about society, identity, gender, economy, and regional experience. Disagreement does not mean that all interpretations are equally valid. Strong explanations remain accountable to evidence, acknowledge uncertainty, and distinguish documented facts from later legend. Presenting multiple perspectives allows the event to remain historically specific while explaining why it continues to matter in Georgian public life.";
    }

    $significance = "WIDER SIGNIFICANCE FOR GEORGIAN HISTORY\n{$title} belongs to a history marked by both regional diversity and repeated efforts at cultural or political connection. Georgian identity was formed through language, Christianity, shared literary traditions, royal institutions, local customs, and memories of particular landscapes, yet none of these elements remained unchanged. Western and eastern kingdoms sometimes competed; mountain communities retained distinct practices; border regions linked several cultures; and foreign rule could produce accommodation as well as resistance. The subject should therefore be understood without assuming that the modern nation-state already existed in its present form. At the same time, later Georgians genuinely used earlier texts, monuments, dynasties, and sacred places to imagine community and continuity. This double perspective—respecting the past on its own terms while tracing its later reception—explains why the subject can carry archaeological, artistic, religious, political, and emotional importance at once.";

    $study = "QUESTIONS FOR FURTHER STUDY\nA detailed archive entry should open research rather than close it. Useful questions include: Which parts of the account are contemporary, and which come from later tradition? Who created the surviving evidence, for what audience, and whose experience is missing? How did the geography of {$location} shape movement, defense, production, worship, or trade? What changed during {$period}, and what continued underneath political change? How have excavation, conservation, translation, or museum display altered modern understanding? Students can compare maps, inscriptions, objects, architecture, chronicles, and modern scholarship, noting where they agree or conflict. They should also examine vocabulary: names such as Colchis, Iberia, Kartli, Egrisi, Abkhazia, and Georgia can refer to different territories in different centuries. Careful questions turn {$title} from a memorized label into a case study in how historical knowledge is produced.";

    return implode("\n\n", [
        $overview,
        $setting,
        $sources,
        $geography,
        $material,
        $comparison,
        $preservation,
        $significance,
        $study,
    ]);
};
